James Rising's research program focuses on interdisciplinary and collaborative studies to understand climate impacts, land use, fisheries, health, transportation, tipping points, and environmental equity. He employs quantitative techniques from various fields and aims to develop systems perspectives. His research aims to improve our understanding of appropriate actions under environmental uncertainty and develop detailed transition pathways for economic and environmental sustainability. One integral aspect of his work is bridging gaps between climate science, biophysical modeling, and climate economics. He collaborates with the Climate Impact Lab (CIL) to quantify climate risks and has developed innovative tools for handling climate vulnerability and risk estimation. His research also incorporates complexity and integrated modeling, particularly in the food system and water analysis. Overall, James Rising's research contributes to interdisciplinary consensus-building and provides valuable insights for researchers and policymakers.
